<headline>Special Weather Statement issued February 19 at 12:40AM EST  by NWS Detroit</headline>
<description>...HIGH WIND AND BURSTS OF SNOW MOVE THROUGH WITH A POWERFUL
ARCTIC COLD FRONT...
WEATHER...
* The combination of wind gusts around 50 mph and bursts of snow
showers move through with a powerful arctic cold front early
this morning. The peak in snow activity coincides with passage
of the front, from about 1 AM to 3 AM, while high wind lasts
through the morning.
* Localized snow accumulation of up to 1 inch is possible before
snow showers taper off after 3 AM.
IMPACTS...
* Snow and blowing snow lead to hazardous driving conditions on
untreated surfaces particularly on bridges, exit ramps and
overpasses.
* Very low visibility to near whiteout conditions for motorists.
* Wind damage to unsecured outdoor objects.
&amp;&amp;
PRECAUTIONARY/PREPAREDNESS ACTIONS...
* Motorists are urged to use caution and account for the poor
driving conditions by slowing down and allowing extra space
between vehicles.
* Prepare, plan and stay informed. Visit http://go.usa.gov/c7kkP</description>
